<seg id="617">5. Conclusions</seg>
<seg id="618">The cooperation of the two audit bodies has proven itself.</seg>
<seg id="619">This resulted in necessary insights into the systems applied in both countries: • intra-Community turnover, • risk management at the USt, particularly with regard to the selection of risky turnover, • recovery of VAT receivables and • VAT audit of large companies.</seg>
<seg id="620">The audit revealed differences in strategies for detecting VAT fraud and the systems explained above.</seg>
<seg id="621">These findings can be used to improve existing procedures.</seg>
<seg id="622">They can also be used to initiate a discussion among interested bodies on which audit approaches and strategies to combat fraud can be used. This applies, for example, to the relationship within and between the Member States and the EU Commission.</seg>
<seg id="623">The experience and insights gained should encourage us to continue to jointly examine the administration of the VAT.</seg>
<seg id="624">6. communique</seg>
<seg id="625">The report was produced in Czech, English and German and signed by the presidents of the Czech Court of Auditors and the Federal Court of Auditors.</seg>
